POINTS:
- [core-feature-pack/common/src/main/resources/content/bin/domain.sh:29] You're right, somehow I was assuming that these arguments were being passed via PROCESS_CONTROLLER_JAVA_OPTS. Let's keep it as it is then. I'm resolving this.
- [core-feature-pack/common/src/main/resources/content/bin/standalone.bat:58] Nice !, thanks
- [testsuite/scripts/src/test/java/org/wildfly/scripts/test/StandaloneScriptTestCase.java:114] Sadly, this is not going to work. We cannot re-use this StandaloneScriptTest, its `testScript` is already messed up testing different cases and the use case to test the -v, -h and friends does not fit well here out of the box.

The ScriptTestCase method  is annotated with @BeforeClass invokes ServerConfigurator.configure(), which is expecting to have a fully started server to configure the log and other stuff, but our use case starting the server with -v or -h will never start a running server, it will just start the server to get some information, so the serve never will never be configured and the test will fail. It passes now because of the order of executions of the other tests.

I look closely at how these tests behave and sketched one as a guide about what I think we will need to do:

```
@RunWith(Parameterized.class)
public class StandaloneHelpVersionScriptTestCase extends ScriptTestCase {
    private static final String STANDALONE_BASE_NAME = "standalone";

    // skip execution of @BeforeClass parent, needs to make the field public at ServerConfigurator
    static {
        ServerConfigurator.CONFIGURED.set(true);
    }

    @Parameter
    public String arg;

    public StandaloneHelpVersionScriptTestCase() {
        super(STANDALONE_BASE_NAME);
    }

    @Parameters
    public static Collection<Object> data() {
        return List.of("-v", "-h"); /// add the remainder ones 
    }

    @Override
    void testScript(final ScriptProcess script) throws InterruptedException, TimeoutException, IOException {
        script.start(null, Map.of(), new String [] {arg});
        final var stdout = script.getStdoutAsString();
        Assert.assertTrue("Expected to find -Xmx16m in the JVM parameters for a version command.", stdout.contains("-Xmx16m\n"));
    }
}
```
I've not checked the domain mode variant, but I guess it will be a similar approach. The idea will be to create those two: StandaloneHelpVersionScriptTestCase and DomainHelpVersionScriptTestCase.

The tests will be parametrized with all the arguments modified in this PR (-v, -V, --version, -h ... and so on). The ScriptTestCase will take care of running each test on each shell if it is available in the current environment.

These scripts are tricky, and having a test case covering them in all the shells helps a lot since we will be exercising them across Windows and Linux when they are running in our CI.

I hope this can guide you, fell free to open a new Jira if you want someone else to take care of the test case. 

Without manually testing your changes across all the different environments, my feeling is the issue is already well done and fixed, adding the test will allow us to remove this manual testing, but we can take care of it if that's your preference (I don't know how complex the domain one will be since I have not checked it)

